Astra, Bank Negara, Medco, Energi Mega: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-03-23T01:44:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-23/astra-bank-negara-medco-energi-mega-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  declined less than 0.1 percent
to 3,517.72.  Energy companies: Crude oil for May delivery in  New York 
traded near a two-week high, rising 0.2 percent to $105.14 a
barrel in after-hours trading. PT Medco Energi Internasional
(MEDC IJ),  Indonesia ’s biggest listed oil company, fell 0.9
percent to 2,800 rupiah and PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ),
the second largest, declined 0.8 percent to 124 rupiah.  PT Agung Podomoro Land (APLN IJ): The company’s 2010 net
income jumped to 241.9 billion rupiah ($28 million) from 35.1
billion rupiah a year earlier, the property developer said in a
statement published in Investor Daily Indonesia. Revenue more
than doubled to 1.9 trillion rupiah, it said. Agung Podomoro was
unchanged at 320 rupiah.  PT Astra International (ASII IJ): The company’s financing
unit, PT Federal International Finance, is seeking 9 trillion
rupiah of loans from domestic and foreign banks to fund lending
expansion, Investor Daily Indonesia reported, citing Djap Tet
Fa, head of treasury and funding at the unit. Astra, Indonesia’s
biggest automotive retailer, slid 0.2 percent to 55,050 rupiah.  PT  Bank Negara  Indonesia (BBNI IJ): The company’s Islamic-
finance unit, PT Bank BNI Syariah, will open 10 branches this
year as it seeks to boost assets by 50 percent, said BNI Syariah
President Director Rizqullah Thohuri. Bank Negara, Indonesia’s
third-biggest state-owned bank, fell 1.4 percent to 3,575
rupiah.  PT Jasa Marga (JSMR IJ): The toll-road operator has
received commitments from three state-owned banks for as much as
7 trillion rupiah of loans to help finance construction of eight
toll roads,  Bisnis Indonesia  reported, citing President Director
Frans Sunito. Jasa Marga rose 0.8 percent to 3,250 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  